The Congress on Tuesday kick-started its campaign for the GHMC elections with AICC general secretary Digvijaya Singh blowing the bugle and addressing as many as four public meetings.Addressing well-attended gatherings in the Greater Hyderabad Municipal Corporation (GHMC) limits including Aramgarh, Chintal Basti and Begumpet, on the day when nominations were opened up, with the party yet to release its list of contesting candidates.He said the party was in favour of encouraging youth, reserving 50 per cent of the seats for women and identifying and rewarding genuine party workers with tickets who worked at the grassroots for the welfare of people.Mr. Singh underscored the need for unity and defeating the ruling Telangana Rashtra Samithi, the Bharatiya Janata Party, the Majlis-e-Ittehadul Muslimeen and the YSR Congress in the elections and said the success that they would ensure during the GHMC polls would put the party firmly on the path to victory in the 2019 general elections.At the meeting held in Chintal Basti and presided by city party president Danam Nagender, senior leaders including AICC general secretary R.C. Khuntia, Leaders of Opposition Mohd. Ali Shabbir (Legislative Council), K. Jana Reddy (Assembly), MP V. Hanumantha Rao and Pradesh Congress Committee President N. Uttam Kumar Reddy and Working President Mallu Bhatti Vikramarka slammed Minister K.T. Rama Rao for saying he would quit if the TRS did not bag a 100 of the 150 divisions in the GHMC elections.Mr. Digvijaya Singh called Mr. Rama Rao an upstart and went on to say that the Congress was ready to face any challenge if Chief Minister K. Chandrasekhar Rao could throw a similar challenge and say the TRS would get a 100 seats.The senior Congress leader added that the GHMC elections would be a referendum on all of the TRSâ€™s pre-poll promises.